06845nam a22009255i 9780271092287DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20212021pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710922877 a10.1515/97802710922872doi  a(DE-B1597)600785  a(OCoLC)1265463364  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aPSY0070002bisacsh04a616.85/2122300aLooking at Trauma :bA Tool Kit for Clinicians /ced. by Shelley Wall, Lesley Hughes, Abby Hershler, Patricia Nguyen. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (96 p.) :b13 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aGraphic Medicine ;v2300tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface: Thinking Through Comics -- tAcknowledgments -- tFrom concept to comic -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1 Care for the Care Provider -- tChapter 2 Self-Care and Grounding -- tChapter 3 Complex Posttraumatic Stress Disorder (cPTSD) -- tChapter 4 Window of Tolerance -- tChapter 5 The Trigger Scale -- tChapter 6 Parallel Lives -- tChapter 7 The Brain—Three Parts -- tChapter 8 How Trauma Impacts Memory -- tChapter 9 Structural Dissociation -- tChapter 10 Karpman’s Triangle -- tChapter 11 Roles and Re-enactments Hexagon -- tChapter 12 Relationship Grid -- tMoving Ahead0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLooking at Trauma: A Tool Kit for Clinicians is an easy-to-use, engaging resource designed to address the challenges health care professionals face in providing much-needed trauma psychoeducation to clients with histories of childhood trauma. Developed by trauma therapists Abby Hershler and Lesley Hughes in collaboration with artist Patricia Nguyen and biomedical communications specialist Shelley Wall, this book presents twelve trauma treatment models accompanied by innovative comics. The models help clinicians provide practical information about the impacts of trauma to their clients—and support those clients in understanding and managing their distressing symptoms.Topics covered include complex posttraumatic stress disorder, stress disorder, emotion regulation, memory, relationship patterns, and self-care. Each chapter features step-by-step instructions on how to use the treatment models with clients; practical educational tips from experienced clinicians in the field of childhood trauma; interactive trauma education comics; a foundational framework focused on care for the provider; and references for further study.Intended for use in both therapeutic and classroom settings, this book is a valuable resource for all healthcare workers. In particular, social workers, psychotherapists, spiritual care providers, nurses, occupational therapists, psychologists, primary care physicians, and psychiatrists will find this tool kit indispensable.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 7aPSYCHOLOGY / Clinical Psychology.2bisacsh1 aClark, Carrie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColthoff, Tessa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGiles, Marlene Duarte, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHershler, Abby, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHershler, Abby, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHughes, Lesley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHughes, Lesley, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLee-Evoy, Janet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacRae, Sue, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcCallum, Nancy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiles, Holly, econtributor.4